Solve the following equation for $a$

$$
\begin{align*}
    \sum_{k=a}^{a+35} \log_{13} \left(\frac{k+1}{k}\right)&=1
\end{align*}
$$

list.markScheme:
First we will unpack the sigma notation.
The smallest value of $k$ is $\textcolor{red}{a}$. This value is the increased by $1$ for each subsequent term.

$$
\begin{align*}
    \sum_{k=a}^{a+35} \log_{13} \left(\frac{k+1}{k}\right)&=\log_{13} \left(\frac{\textcolor{red}{a}+1}{\textcolor{red}{a}}\right)+\log_{13} \left(\frac{\textcolor{red}{a+1}+1}{\textcolor{red}{a+1}}\right)+\\[6pt]
    &\hspace{1.2em}\log_{13} \left(\frac{\textcolor{red}{a+2}+1}{\textcolor{red}{a+2}}\right)+...
\end{align*}
$$

This continues until we reach the largest value of $k$ which is $a+35$.

$$
\begin{align*}
    +...\log_{13} \left(\frac{\textcolor{red}{a+34}+1}{\textcolor{red}{a+34}}\right)+\log_{13} \left(\frac{\textcolor{red}{a+35}+1}{\textcolor{red}{a+35}}\right) \tag*{\textbf{(M1)}}
\end{align*}
$$

If we simplify the fractions and then apply the following log law

$$
\begin{align*}
    \log_{a}\tfrac{x}{y}&=\log_{a}x-\log_{a}y
\end{align*}
$$

We get

$$
\begin{align*}
    \sum_{k=a}^{a+35} \log_{13} \left(\frac{k+1}{k}\right)&=\log_{13} \left(\frac{a+1}{a}\right)+\log_{13} \left(\frac{a+2}{a+1}\right)+...\log_{13} \left(\frac{a+36}{a+35}\right)\\[6pt]
    &=\cancel{\log_{13}{(a+1)}}-\textcolor{blue}{\log_{13}{a}}+\cancel{\log_{13}{(a+2)}}-\cancel{\log_{13}{(a+1)}}+\\[6pt]
    &\hspace{1.2em}-\cancel{\log_{13}{(a+2)}}+...+\textcolor{blue}{\log_{13}{(a+36)}}-\cancel{\log_{13}{(a+35)}} \tag*{\textbf{(M1)}}
\end{align*}
$$

Notice how the terms cancel each other out, leaving only the two $\textcolor{blue}{\text{blue}}$ terms. Recall, from the question, this is equal to $1$.

$$
\begin{align*}
    -\log_{13}{a}+\log_{13}{(a+36)}&=1 \tag*{\textbf{A1}}
\end{align*}
$$

We can now solve the equation by rewriting the L.H.S. as a single logarithm

$$
\begin{align*}
    \log_{13}{\left(\frac{a+36}{a}\right)}&=1
\end{align*}
$$

Using the definition of a logarithm, we rewrite the equation into exponential form

$$
\begin{align*}
    \frac{a+36}{a}&=13^1 \tag*{\textbf{A1}}
\end{align*}
$$

Now we can solve for $a$

$$
\begin{align*}
    a+36&=13a\\[6pt]
    12a&=36\\[6pt]
    &\hspace{-0.8em}\answer{a=3} \tag*{\textbf{A1}}
\end{align*}
$$

